5.3.1 Degrees of freedom
The number of independent coordinates required to describe mo-

In general, the number of degrees of freedom is given by,
for 3D

5.10 Phase Space Trajectory**
The relation between position and conjugate momentum for the given value of energy is deﬁned as ’phase curve’.
5.10.1 Properties of phase space
(i) For time-independent Hamiltonians, the phase curves never intersect each other.
(ii) Phase curve may be closed, open or unbounded curve.
(iii) Classical phase curve means we are plotting the phase curve for the given energy E.
(iv) The state of classical mechanical system is precisely determined since there is not any uncertainty principle in CM.
(v) The path of classical phase trajectory is well deﬁned.
(vi) For the system with n degrees of freedom, the phase space will be 2n-dimensional.
5.10.2 Steps to draw phase-space trajectory
(i) Draw the potential in which the particle is moving
(ii) Draw classically allowed lines (E ≥ V (x)). Among the lines, mark the special cases E < 0, E > 0 and E = 0 including
maxima and minima of V (x). Among the marked lines, mark the region where E ≥ V (x).
(iii) Project the potentials in the x − p
x
plane. The projection of closed region with stable equilibrium point gives closed loop.
Unclosed region or decreasing potential gives parabolic or hyperbolic type graph.
(iv) The phase trajectories follow the directions given below.
(v) Diagram will be symmetric about X-axis ignoring direction.
(vi) If V (x) even, the trajectory will be symmetric about both X and Y-axis ignoring the direction.

12.2 Zeeman Effect

It is of two types depending on spin
(i) Normal Zeeman effect
(ii) Anomalous Zeeman effect

Dirac Equation
So far we’ve only discussed scalar ﬁelds such that under a Lorentz transformation n, the ﬁeld transforms as
quantization of such ﬁelds gives rise to spin 0 particles. But most particles in Nature have an intrinsic angular momentum, or
spin. These arise naturally in ﬁeld theory by considering ﬁelds which themselves transform non-trivially under the Lorentz group.
In this section we will describe the Dirac equation, whose quantization gives rise to fermionic spin 1=2 particles.

21.2 Perturbation Theory in Interacting Field Theory
The equation of motion coming from the above Lagrange cannot be solved exactly. We will try to solve this equation using pertur-
bation theory. To ensure that the additional terms are small perturbations, we might think that the condition λ
n
<< 1 should be
satisﬁed. But it’s not true. The dimension of λ
n
plays a role in the condition.
The various terms, parameterized by λ
n
, fall into three different categories:
1. [λ
3
] = 1: For this term, the dimensionless parameter is λ
3
/E = 1, where E has dimension of mass. Typically in quantum
ﬁeld theory, E is the energy scale of the process of interest. This means that
at high energies E >> λ
3

3
ϕ

at low energies E << λ
3

because they’re most relevant at low energies (which, after all, is where most of the physics we see lies). In a relativistic
theory, E > m, so we can always make this perturbation small by taking λ
3
<< m.
2. [λ
4
] = 0: this term is small if λ
4
<< 1. Such perturbations are called marginal.
3. [λ
n
] < 0 for n >= 5: The dimensionless parameter is (λ
n
E
n−4
), which is small at low-energies and large at high energies.
Such perturbations are called irrelevant.
It is typically impossible to avoid high energy processes in quantum ﬁeld theory. This means that we might expect problems with
irrelevant operators. Indeed, these lead to ”non-renormalizable” ﬁeld theories in which one cannot make sense of the inﬁnities at
arbitrarily high energies. This doesn’t necessarily mean that the theory is useless; just that it is incomplete at some energy scale.
The naive assignment of relevant, marginal and irrelevant is not always ﬁxed. Quantum corrections can sometimes change the
character of an operator.

Example: Gamow’s Theory of Alpha Decay
Gamow provided the ﬁrst succesful explanation of alpha decay (the spontaneous of an alpha-particle by certain radioactive
nuclei)
Since the α-particle carries a positive charge (2e), it will be elctrically repelled by the leftover nucleus (charge Ze), as soon as it
gets far enough away to escape the nuclear binding force. But, ﬁrst it has to cross a barrier is more than the emitted alpha particle.
Gamow approximated the potential energy by a ﬁnite square well (representing the attractive nuclear force), extending out to r
1
(the nucleus), joined to a repulsive Coulomb potential. He identiﬁed the escape mechanism as quantum tunneling.
